{
  "texts": [
    "More specifically, when θ = 0 d ⊕ 1 and c = 0, (1) becomes the base judge's score b.",
    "While this is certainly true, we also prove in Section D.2 that this happens with a high probability when learning θ.",
    "We learn the judge by minimizing the squared loss, which lends the judge its name.",
    "Specifically, we minimize a regularized squared loss",
    ", where e t is the base judge's rationale, b t is its score, and s t is the human score in data point t ∈ [n]."
  ]
}